Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: *See Plea/Sentencing Hearing docket*
Same as Complaint just removing the Repeater enhancer.

(11:01 AM cases 21CF680, 21CF1151, 21CF1328, 22CF158, 21TR8565, 21TR8566 called.) Defendant Nathaniel J. Gomez in court, in custody. Attorney Roger M Hillestad in court for Nathaniel J. Gomez. Prosecuting Attorney Matthew Z Kirkpatrick in court for the State of Wisconsin.
Agreement has been reached and is recited by counsel. 
Defendant pleads No Contest to 21CF680 Count 1: Driver or Operate a Motor Vehicle Without Owner's Consent without Repeater, 21CF1151 Count 1: Felony Bail Jumping without Repeater, Count 2: Possession of Drug Paraphernalia without Repeater, 21CF1328 Count 1: Felony Bail Jumping without Repeater and Count 3: Possession of Drug Paraphernalia without Repeater.
Defendant waives right to a preliminary hearing in 22CF158 and Court accepts waiver.
State will file an Information in 22CF158 which will mirror the complaint, but will be without the Repeater enhancer to coincide with plea agreement. Attorney Hillestad has no objection to proceeding without the Information on file, knowing it will be filed today.
Defendant pleads No Contest to 22CF158 Count 1: Felony Bail Jumping without Repeater.
Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. 
Court accepts the defendant's No Contest pleas and finds the defendant Guilty of 21CF680 Count 1 without Repeater, 21CF1151 Count 1 without Repeater, Count 2 without Repeater, 21CF1328 Count 1 without Repeater, Count 3 without Repeater and 22CF158 Count 1 without Repeater.

Court orders sentences as follows: 
21CF680 Count 1: Court imposes and stays 12 months jail with Huber privileges if jail determines eligible with 127 days credit. Court places the defendant on probation for 2 years with conditions. Court orders all counts are concurrent.
21CF1151 Count 1: Court imposes and stays 12 months jail with Huber privileges if jail determines eligible with 124 days credit. Court places the defendant on probation for 2 years with conditions. Court orders all counts are concurrent.
21CF1328 Count 1: Court imposes and stays 12 months jail with Huber privileges if jail determines eligible with 95 days credit. Court places the defendant on probation for 2 years with conditions. Court orders all counts are concurrent.
22CF158 Count 1: Court imposes and stays 12 months jail with Huber privileges if jail determines eligible with 94 days credit. Court places the defendant on probation for 2 years with conditions. Court orders all counts are concurrent.

Court orders conditions of probation as follows:
120 days jail with Huber privileges if jail determines eligible, stayed pending further order of the Court on 21CF680 Count 1. AODA and follow through with recommendations. Maintain absolute sobriety. No contact with D.S., A.C., J.D. without their approval and the approval of the Probation Agent. No contact with any known drug dealers/users, except in a therapeutic setting. Any conditions, programming or treatment per the agent and follow through with recommendations. Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge and pay court costs to include 4 bench warrant fees in 21CF680. Any remaining charges and cases 21TR8565, 21TR8566 are dismissed and read in.

Court orders sentence on 21CF1151 Count 2 and 21CF1328 Count 3 as follows:
Defendant to provide DNA sample and pay surcharge and pay court costs. Any remaining charges are dismissed and read in.
Letter from Defendant to Court regarding late appearance and request amend bond.

Conditions: 
No contact with co-defendant E.P.
No contact with anyone involved in illegal drug activities, except in a therapeutic setting. 
No acts or threats of violence against D.S.
Defendant to maintain absolute sobriety. 
Defendant not to consume/possess any alcohol or go into any taverns, bars, liquor stores/place where alcohol is primarily served/sold. 
Defendant not to consume/use/possess any illegal drugs/non-prescribed medications/controlled substances or drug paraphernalia. 
Comply with Pre-Trial Monitoring Services. 
Not to discuss pending litigation with D.S.
Covers 21CF1151, 21CF1328, 21CF680, 22CF158.
($1,000.00 previously posted, will need to post an addition $1,000.00)

3:26 PM cases 21CF680, 21CF1151, 21CF1328, 22CF158 called. Prosecuting attorney Peter J. Rindal in court for the State of Wisconsin.  Defendant Nathaniel J. Gomez in court.  Attorney Roger M Hillestad appeared by phone for Nathaniel J. Gomez. A warrant was ordered at 1:30 PM stayed until 4:15 PM today. Warrant will not be issued. 
Defendant requests a new attorney to be appointed through the SPD office- Court denies the request for a new attorney. 
Court has a colloquy with the defendant regarding going to trial. Defendant would like to proceed to trial. 
State asks for a $5,000 cash bond citing previous missed appearances. 
Defense responds. Court orders a $1,000 cash bond to cover all files in addition to the already posted $1,000 cash bond. 
Defendant taken into custody. 
Trial (in 21CF680) to remain on the calendar.

(Cases 21CF680, 21CF1151, 21CF1328, 22CF158 are called at 1:38 PM) No appearance by Defendant Nathaniel J. Gomez.  Attorney Roger M Hillestad in court for Nathaniel J. Gomez.  Attorney Matthew Z Kirkpatrick in court for State of Wisconsin. 
Defense indicates the last he knew the Defendant was in custody. State indicates he bonded out of jail. State requests warrant given the Defendant's unknown whereabouts and requests the trial be removed. Defense requests warrant be stayed until end of the business today. 
Court orders warrant effective today at 4:15 PM - trial remains on the calendar until Attorney Hillestad lets the State know if he can contact his client.
